1 What is the analysis about?

  • The following data analysis seeks to determine two significant findings associated to the effectiveness of advertising and promotions at General Mills cereal producer.

6 What is common between two different data set?

  • It’s non other than UPC #Now lets join theese two different data set with the help of UPC using left join.

7 Replacing the string

7.1 Replacing the string “.” of the UPC by “-” in the sales data.

#lets say the newly join data be data3

data3<- productdata%>%
  mutate(UPC = str_replace_all(UPC,"-","."))%>%
  mutate(UPC = substr(UPC,4,17))%>%
  mutate(UPC = as.factor(UPC))

#Replace "." of the UPC by "-"

8 Joining two data set

8.1 left-join

data3 <- salesdata%>%
  left_join(data3, by = "UPC")
  
#reset data set count
salesdata <- data3

10 Basic EDA

grid.arrange(
  salesdata %>% 
    ggplot(aes(week)) +
      geom_bar(),
  salesdata %>% 
    ggplot(aes(price)) +
      geom_bar(),
  salesdata %>% 
    ggplot(aes(units)) +  
      geom_bar(),
  salesdata %>% 
    ggplot(aes(volume)) +
      geom_bar(),
  salesdata %>%
    ggplot(aes(promo)) +
    geom_bar()
)

  • The above graphs and charts provides the general idea of unit sales, promo, price and volumes.

11 Relationship between product units and price

  • There is an inverse relationship between price and the product quantity. As the quantity increases price decreases.

12 Units sold and Brand associated with them

salesdata%>%
    ggplot(aes(brand, y=units, fill = brand))+ geom_bar(stat="identity")+ ggtitle ("Average Unit sold per brand")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())

+ Wow!! looks like kellog frosted flakes is the most sold product.

13 What flavors are most popular?

salesdata %>%
    ggplot(aes(flavor, y=units, fill = flavor)) + geom_histogram(stat="identity")+ coord_flip()+ ggtitle ("Average Unit sold per flavor")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: binwidth, bins, pad

  • Regular flavor is the most liked whereas Cocoa is the least favourite among people.

16 Detailed EDA

17 How do promo effect units sold and price?

salesdata %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = units, y = price, fill = promo)) + ggtitle ("promo effect on units sold and price") + geom_density(stat = "identity")

+ Average product Price increases with increase on promo

18 How do ads effect units sold and price?

salesdata %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = units, y = price, fill = ad)) + ggtitle ("promo effect on units sold and ad") + geom_bar(stat = "identity")

+ price increses for the maller unit + diminishing price for the larger units

#Effects of ad and promo on average unit sold

salesdata%>%
  group_by(ad, promo)%>%
  summarise(Average_Unit_sold = mean(units))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = promo, y = Average_Unit_sold, fill = ad))+  ggtitle ("Effects of ad and promo on average unit sold") +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge')

+ there is a significant difference between average unit sold with promo and without promo. + Big and small size ads have similar effects. + + total sales increases as ads and promo combine. However, there will not be a significant diference in sales if promo is removed.

19 Effects of ad and promo quantities less than 5

salesdata%>%
  group_by(ad, promo)%>%
  #filter(units < 5)%>%
  summarise(Average_Unit_sold = mean(units))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = promo, y = Average_Unit_sold, fill = ad))+  ggtitle ("Effects of ad and promo for units less than 5") +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge')

+ on average The effects of size of ad on products less than 5 with no promo are almost equivalent. + However High ad with promo plays bigger role in selling more products than the medium and no ad at all. +

19.0.1 Effects of ad and promo quantities greater than 5

salesdata%>%
  group_by(ad, promo)%>%
  filter(units > 5 )%>%
  summarise(Average_Unit_sold= mean(units))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = promo, y = Average_Unit_sold, fill = ad))+ ggtitle ("Effects of ad and promo quantities greater than 5") +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge')

  • Medium/small ad is more effective for the units more than 5
  • Ads with promo leads the sales
salesdata%>%
  group_by(week, promo)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = week, y = promo, color = promo,))+  ggtitle ("Effectiveness of promo over the weeks") +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')

salesdata%>%
  group_by(week, ad)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = week, y = promo, color = ad,))+ ggtitle ("Effects of promo and ad over the weeks") +
  geom_jitter(stat = 'identity')

+ ads with no promo have very little effect

20 Statistical EDA

20.1 Does sales increases with increase in promo and ad?

  • What relation do ads and promo have on total sales?

20.2 statistical test of sales and promo=“yes”

#statistical test for unit sales and promo
t.test(salesdata$units[salesdata$promo == "Yes"])
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  salesdata$units[salesdata$promo == "Yes"]
## t = 102.06, df = 4544, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.98162 11.41178
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##   11.1967

+confidence interval is not “0” +p-value < 2.2e-16
